          <h3>Here is a timeline of John M. Keynes life:</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>1883</strong> - Born in Cambridge, England.</li>
            <li><strong>1909</strong> - Publishes his first professional economic article in the <em>Economics Journal</em> about the effect of a recent global economic downturn on India.</li>
            <li><strong>1911</strong> - Became editor of the <em>Economic Journal</em>.</li>
            <li><strong>1919</strong> - Wrote the <em>Economic Consequences of the Peace</em>, which accurately predicted the difficulties Germany would have following the <em>Treaty of Versailles</em>.</li>
            <li><strong>1922</strong> - Advocated reduction of German reparations with <em>A Revision of the Treaty</em>.</li>
            <li><strong>1924</strong> - Adocated a fiscal response, where the government could create jobs by spending on public works.</li>
            <li><strong>1931</strong> - Criticized Ramsay McDonald's austerity budget which cut public investment, wages and increased taxes.</li>
            <li><strong>1936</strong> - <em>The General theory of Employment, Interest and Money</em> provided a framework for macroeconomics and was a radical depature from the more limited classical framework.</li>
            <li><strong>1937</strong> - Limited participation in theoretical debates following the publication of the <em>General Theory</em> due to continued health issues.</li>
            <li><strong>1946</strong> - Dies of a heart attack at the age of 62.</li>
          </ul>
